Source: https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/reference/react-dom/components/form.md

This example illustrates how to gracefully handle errors that occur during a React form submission by wrapping the `<form>` element in an `ErrorBoundary` component. If the function specified in the form's `action` prop throws an error, the `ErrorBoundary`'s defined fallback UI is displayed to the user, preventing the application from crashing. This approach ensures a robust user experience when dealing with potential submission failures.

```javascript
import { ErrorBoundary } from "react-error-boundary";

export default function Search() {
  function search() {
    throw new Error("search error");
  }
  return (
    <ErrorBoundary
      fallback={<p>There was an error while submitting the form</p>}
    >
      <form action={search}>
        <input name="query" />
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
      </form>
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}
```

